<section id="html">
    <div class="tutorial">
        <h1>HTML</h1>
        <div class="tutorialSubheading">
            <h2>What Is HTML?</h2>
        </div>
        <p>
            <li>HTML is a programming language that defines the content on a
            website.</li>
            <li>HTML stands for Hyper Text Markup Language</li>
            <li>A markup language is one that defines the elements within a
            document using tags.</li>
        </p>
        <div class="tutorialSubheading">
            <h2>Tags</h2>
        </div>
        <p>
        <li>Tags are contained by angled braces, like this <code>&ltnameOfTag&gt.</code>
                The closing tag starts with an angled brace, followed by a forward slash,
        followed by another angled brace: <code>&lt/nameOfTag&gt.</code> In between the closing
                and opening tag is the content that you want to be displayed on the page.</li>
        <li>Some examples of tags are the header two tag: <code>&lth2&gt&lt/h2&gt,</code>
                the image tag: <code> &ltimg src="whateverTheImgSrcIs"/&gt </code>(the image tage is self closing), and
                the hyperlink tag that links one page to another: <code>&lta href="whateverTheAHrefIs"&gt&lt/&gt </code></li>
            <li>Don't worry if you're a bit confused, getting used to the syntax of
            programming can be difficult at first. Keep reading for a closer look at these different tags.</li>
        </p>
        <div class="tutorialSubheading">
            <h2>The <code>h2</code> Tag</h2>
        </div>
        <p>
            <li><code> h2 </code> stands for header two in this tag. Header two simply means
            that this tag is a header and is the second smallest type of header.</li>
            <li>You type text in between the opening and closing tag like so: <code>
            &lth2&gtHello World!&lt/h2&gt. </code> The text appears like this on the page:
            Hello World!
            </li>
        </p>
        <div class="tutorialSubheading">
            <h2>The <code> img </code> Tag</h2>
        </div>
        <p>
            <li>The <code> img </code> tag displays an image on the page and looks like this
                in code: <code> &ltimg src="imgSrc"/&gt. </code> The image tag
                is self closing, so the forward slash is placed at the end of the opening tag.</li>
        </p>
        <div class="tutorialSubheading">
            <h2>The <code> div </code> Tag</h2>
        </div>
        <p>
            <li>The <code> div </code> tag is one of the most important tags in HTML and
            looks like this in code: <code> &ltdiv class="className"&gt&lt/div&gt.</code>
            <code>div</code> is short for division, and the <code>div</code> tag encapsulates
            elements on the page and divides the HTML document into
            sections.</li>
            <li>The <code>div</code> tag also allows a programmer to group together
            HTML elements and apply CSS styles to many elements at once.</li>
            <li>The class of the div goes in between the quotes. Programmers
            can name classes what they choose, but it has to be logical and
            follow programming conventions.</li>
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

<section id="css">
    <div class="tutorial">
        <h1>CSS</h1>
        <div class="tutorialSubheading">
            <h2>What is CSS?</h2>
        </div>
        <p>
            <li>CSS stands for cascading style sheets.</li>
            <li>CSS describes how HTML elements are to be
            displayed on a page.</li>
            <li>CSS code has the name of a tag, such as <code>h2</code>, followed
                by two curly braces (<code>{}</code>). Inside the curly braces is
            information about how that element is going to be
            displayed on the page.</li>
        <li>For example, inside the curly braces <code>h2 {code to modify how content is displayed}</code> a programmer could
                change the color of all the <code> h2 </code> tags on a site to blue by coding <code>color: blue; </code></li>
            <li>To be more specific about a change, a programmer can use a div. A dot precedes
            the name of the div's class. If it pertains to the h1 tag in that class, for example the programmer
            would type: <code>.className h1 {code to modify how h1 content in div class
                    className is displayed} </code></li>
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

